I"¾<p>Prediction and choice are a root of uncertainty for all life, because all living things perceive, decide, and act in order to survive. This feedback loop between an organism and its environment is a continuous work-in-progress. On the evolutionary playing field, success is never final, but failure can indeed be fatal. In this game of survival, uncertainty is a close ally. An associate in times of crisis. An accomplice in the arena of life. Although this relationship is universal in all living beings, there are differences in how organisms manage prediction and choice. A useful framework is one coined by Daniel Dennett. He calls it the <strong>Four Creatures of Evolution</strong>:</p>

